order to keep pace with his schedule. This fast-paced ministry affectionately earned him the nickname of \"Hurricane Charlie.\" Therefore, BMCHS is the home of the \"Hurricanes.\" The school's inaugural principal was Jane Moerschbacher, who held the position until she retired in 2007. The school's current principal is Camille Jowanna, who, as a 7th grader, received the Sacrament of [[Confirmation]] from the school's namesake, Bishop McLaughlin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bmchs.com/about-bishop/our-staff/|title=Our Staff|accessdate=April 25, 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==Academics==\nBishop McLaughlin Catholic High School is ranked as the 7th Best Catholic High School in the state of Florida for 2020, as rated by NICHE, with an overall grade of \"A.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.niche.com/k12/bishop-mclaughlin-catholic-high-school-spring-hill-fl/|title=2020 Best Catholic High Schools in Florida|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> BMCHS is experiencing continued growth and is known for its high academic standards, use of technology in the classroom, sports program and fine arts program. In 2017, BMCHS\u2019s STREAM (Science, Technology, Religion, Engineering, Art and Math) Club won the Innovations in Catholic Education Technology Integration Award for its work in three dimensional printing of prosthetic hands for children with limited upper limb mobility as a result of birth defect or injury,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.catholicteacher.com/2017-innovation-catholic-education-technology-integration-finalists/|title=2017 Innovation in Catholic Education \u201cTechnology Integration\u201d Finalists|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref> and was also honored by District Administration magazine as part of its Schools of TechXcellence program for this work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prweb.com/releases/2017/06/prweb14378818.htm/|title=District Administration, HP and Intel Name 19 schools of TechXcellence|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nxtbook.com/pmg/DA/TechX_0617/index.php#/16|title=3D Printing: Service to Our Community|accessdate=March 26, 2019}}</ref> BMCHS is also one of the few private high schools in the [[Tampa Bay area]] to offer an Exceptional Student Education (ESE) program.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bmchs.com/academics/ese-program/|title=Exceptional Student Education (ESE) Program|accessdate=April 25, 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==Financial Aid==\nBishop McLaughlin Catholic High School offers various forms of financial assistance. Diocesan assistance includes the Catholic School Tuition Assistance Grant (C-STAG), Mary C. Forbes Foundation Scholarships and grants from the Catholic Foundation. BMCHS also accepts government-managed scholarships such as [[Step Up For Students]], Gardiner Scholarships, AAA Scholarships and McKay Scholarships. BMCHS also manages several privately funded scholarships.<ref name=bmchs>{{cite web|url=http://www.bmchs.com/admissions/bishop-facts/|title=BMCHS Hurricanes Q & A|accessdate=April 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics=\nBishop McLaughlin Catholic High School's athletic program is a Division 3A participating member of the [[Florida High School Athletic Association]] ([[FHSAA]]). BMCHS offers participation in competitive sports such as Football, Boys Basketball, Girls Basketball, Boys Baseball, Girls Softball, Girls Volleyball, Boys Boys Soccer, Girls Soccer, Swimming, Track & Field, Cross-Country Running, Tennis and Cheerleading. Many of the coaches at BMCHS have played their sport at the college and professional level. Former professional players include Head Football Coach [[Ken Stills]], who played safety for the [[University of Wisconsin]] and professionally with the [[Green Bay Packers]] and [[Minnesota Vikings]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/player/kenstills/2526590/profile|title=NFL Player Profile|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bishopmclaughlinathletics.com/2020/04/06/2020-varsity-football-message-head-football-ken-stills-sr/|title=2020 Varsity Football Message \u2013 Head Football Coach Ken Stills Sr.|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>; Varsity Boys Head Basketball Coach [[Derrick Sharp]], who played point and shooting guard for the [[University of South Florida]] and professionally for 18 years with various teams in the [[Israeli Premier League]] and [[EuroLeague]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bishopmclaughlinathletics.com/2020/04/17/bishop-mclaughlin-appoints-new-head-basketball-coach-2020-5a-hillsborough-county-coach-of-the-year/|title=Bishop McLaughlin appoints new Head Basketball Coach \u2013 2020 5A Hillsborough County Coach of the Year|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>; and former Assistant Football Coach [[Keith Tandy]], who played safety for [[West Virginia University]] and professionally with the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] and [[Atlanta Falcons]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/player/keithtandy/2534741/profile|title=NFL Player Profile|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suncoastnews.com/sports/ex-buccaneer-tandy-headed-back-to-team/article_4aa1b8d0-6ecb-11ea-95e5-ab38cf2218c1.html|title=Ex-Buccaneer Tandy headed back to team|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> Known as \"Thee Beach at Bishop,\" BMCHS also has one of the largest [[Beach Volleyball]] facilities in [[Florida]], including 10 regulation size sand volleyball courts, which was constructed by Varsity Volleyball Coach Doug Chinchar who played volleyball at [[The Ohio State University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tampabay.com/sports/high-schools/2019/04/24/dig-this-beach-volleyball-gains-popularity-locally-no-ocean-needed/|title=Dig this: Beach volleyball gains popularity locally (no ocean needed)|accessdate=April 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bmchs.com/student-life/athletics/teams/sand-volleyball/|title=Sand Volleyball|accessdate=April 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.nonamevbc.com/coaches.html|title=Doug Chinchar|accessdate=April 25, 2020}}</ref>    \n  \n==Performing Arts & Activities==\nBishop McLaughlin's facilities include an 880 seat state-of-the-art theater known as the Eleanor Dempsey Performing Arts Center (EDPAC).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bmchs.com/student-life/athletics/facilities/|title=Facilities|accessdate=April 25, 2020}}</ref> The EDPAC hosts school events (such as plays, musicals, concerts and speaking engagements), and is recognized as being a public entertainment venue by live entertainment ticket sales and distribution companies such as [[Ticketmaster]] and [[Live Nation Entertainment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bmchs.com/student-life/athletics/facilities/|title=Facilities|accessdate=April 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livenation.com/venue/KovZpZA1AtJA/eleanor-dempsey-performing-arts-center-events|title=Eleanor Dempsey Performing Arts Center|accessdate=April 25, 2020}}</ref> Clubs, societies and activities include Student Government, National Honor Society, Yearbook, STEM Club, SADD ([[Students Against Destructive Decisions]]), Key Club, Teen Court, Student Ambassadors, Peer Ministry, Show Choir and Drama Club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bmchs.com/?s=clubs|title=Honor Societies and Clubs|accessdate=April 25, 2020}}</ref> \n\n==Significant dates==\nJanuary 20, 2000 - Diocese acquired the land for the future home of BMCHS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pascoclerk.com/public-sup-svcs-form-or-image-validate.asp?instrument=2000162395/|title=Warranty Deed|date=December 20, 2000|accessdate=October 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nMay 30, 2002 - Construction of the new BMCHS begins.\n\nAugust 11, 2003 - BMCHS welcomed its first freshman class.\n\nMay 29, 2007 - Commencement was held for the school's first graduating senior class.\n\n==Notable alumni==\nNotable alumni of Bishop McLaughlin Catholic High School:\n*[[Nate Pearson]], A BMCHS varsity baseball player (Class of 2015), Nate Pearson was considered one of the top prospects for the [[2017 Major League Baseball draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/prospects/2017?list=draft|title=MLB.com 2017 Prospect Watch|website=Major League Baseball}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/college/nate-pearson-progressing-draft-nears/#zUY0dopGjz80qsAQ.97|title=Nate Pearson Progressing as Draft Nears|last=Belinsky|first=Hudson|work=baseballamerica.com|date=April 12, 2017|accessdate=June 28, 2017}}</ref> Pearson was selected 28th overall by the [[Toronto Blue Jays]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/236004104/blue-jays-draft-pitcher-nate-pearson-at-no-28/|title=Toronto takes hard-throwing Pearson at 28|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=June 13, 2017|accessdate=June 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-select-shortstop-logan-warmoth-first-round-draft-pick/|title=Blue Jays select Warmoth, Pearson with first-round draft picks|last=Nicholson-Smith|first=Ben|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=June 12, 2017|accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref> and signed his contract with the Blue Jays on June 28, 2017, which included a $2.45 million signing bonus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-officially-sign-first-round-picks-warmoth-pearson/|title=Blue Jays officially sign first-round picks Warmoth, Pearson|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=June 28, 2017|accessdate=June 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/237042574/2017-draft-signing-and-bonus-tracker/|title=2017 Draft: Signing and Bonus Tracker|work=MLB.com|accessdate=July 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{official website|http://www.bmchs.com/}}\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Saint Petersburg}}\n{{FHSAA Class 3A}}\n\n[[Category:Private high schools in Florida]]\n[[Category:Catholic secondary schools in Florida]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Diocese of Saint Petersburg]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Florida]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2003]]\n", "name_user": "Mjowanna", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected 2 newspaper article citations to authority.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bishop_McLaughlin_Catholic_High_School"}
{"title_page": "GitLab", "text_new": "{{short description|open-source Git repository host}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Advert|date=June 2018}}\n{{primary sources|date=December 2016}}\n{{More citations needed|date=October 2018}}\n}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name                 = GitLab Inc.\n| logo                 = GitLab logo.svg\n| logo_alt             = GitLab\n| screenshot           = GitLab_running_11.0_(2018-07).png\n| caption              = \n| location             = San Francisco, United States\n| area_served          = [[World]]wide\n| url                  = {{URL|https://gitlab.com}}\n| commercial           = Yes\n| type                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Git]]-repository hosting service\n* Collaborative revision control}}\n| registration         = Optional\n| language             = [[English language|English]]\n| owner                = GitLab Inc.\n| author               = \n| alexa                = {{Decrease}} 2,085 ({{as of|2019|10|27|alt=October 2019}})<ref>{{cite web\n | url        = https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/gitlab.com\n | title      = GitLab.com Alexa Ranking\n | publisher  = Alexa Internet\n | accessdate = 27 October 2019}}</ref>\n| founder              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Sid Sijbrandij]]\n* [[Dmitriy Zaporozhets]]}}\n| key_people           = {{Plainlist|\n* Sid Sijbrandij ([[CEO]])\n* Dmitriy Zaporozhets ([[Chief technology officer|CTO]])}}\n| num_users            = \n| num_employees        = 1,268<ref name=MeetOurTeam>{{cite web\n | url         = https://about.gitlab.com/team\n | title       = GitLab Team\n | access-date = 25 April 2020}}</ref>\n| industry             = [[Software]]\n| programming_language = [[Ruby (programming language)|Ruby]],<ref name=\"Flowers\"/> [[Go (programming language)|Go]], and [[Vue.js]]\n| launch_date          = {{Start date and age|2011}}\n| current_status       = Online\n}}\n\n{{Infobox software\n| name                   = GitLab Application\n| bodystyle              = width:300px\n| screenshot             = \n| caption                = \n| latest release version = 12.10.1\n| latest release date    = {{Start date and age|2020|04|24}}<ref name=\"v12-10-1\">{{cite web\n | url        = https://about.gitlab.com/releases/2020/04/24/gitlab-12-10-1-released/\n | title      = GitLab Patch Release: 12.10.1\n | author     = Robert Speicher\n | publisher  = GitLab\n | date       = 24 April 2020\n | accessdate = 25 April 2020}}</ref>\n| operating system       = [[Cross-platform]]\n| platform               = [[x86-64]], [[ARMhf]]\n| license                = '''Community Edition:''' [[MIT License]] and other free software licenses<ref name=\"ce-license\" /><br />'''Enterprise Edition:''' [[Source-available]] [[proprietary software]]<ref name=\"ce-license\">{{cite web\n | url   = https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/blob/master/LICENSE\n | title = GitLab LICENSE file\n | accessdate = 29 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | url   = https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/blob/master/ee/LICENSE\n | title = GitLab Enterprise Edition LICENSE file\n | accessdate = 29 March 2020}}</ref>\n| programming language   = [[Ruby (programming language)|Ruby]]\n}}\n\n'''GitLab''' is a [[web-based]] [[DevOps]] lifecycle tool that provides a [[Git]]-[[repository (version control)|repository]] manager providing [[wiki]], [[Issue tracking system|issue-tracking]] and [[continuous integration]]/[[continuous deployment]] pipeline<ref name=\":3\">https://about.gitlab.com/features/gitlab-ci-cd/</ref> features, using an [[Open-source software|open-source]] license, developed by GitLab Inc. The software was created by [[Ukrainians]] Dmitriy Zaporozhets and Valery Sizov,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://about.gitlab.com/company/history |title=History of GitLab|website=GitLab|language=en|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref> and is used by several large tech companies including [[Juniper]], [[Cisco]], [[IBM]], [[Sony]], [[J\u00fclich Research Center]], [[NASA]], [[Alibaba]], [[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]], [[Invincea]], [[O'Reilly Media]], [[Leibniz-Rechenzentrum]] (LRZ), [[CERN]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenextweb.com/insider/2014/06/04/github-rival-gitlab-building-business-just-0-1-paying-customers |title=GitLab is building a business with 0.1% of paying customers|last=Degeler|first=Andrii|date=4 June 2014|work=The Next Web}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://information-technology.web.cern.ch/services/cern-commercial|title=Services - CERN or commercial provider?|author=CERN|work=cern.ch}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lrz.de/services/netzdienste/gitlab_en |title=Services - GitLab}}</ref> [[European XFEL]], [[GNOME Foundation]], [[Boeing]], [[Autodata]], [[Nvidia|NVIDIA]], and [[SpaceX]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://venturebeat.com/2015/07/09/y-combinator-backed-github-competitor-gitlab-raises-1-5m |title=Y Combinator-backed GitHub competitor GitLab raises $1.5M|date=2015-07-09|work=VentureBeat|access-date=2018-06-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe code was originally written in [[Ruby (programming language)|Ruby]],<ref name=\"Flowers\">{{cite web|url=https://about.gitlab.com/2018/10/29/why-we-use-rails-to-build-gitlab |title=Why we use Ruby on Rails to build GitLab|last=Flowers|first=Aricka|date=2018-10-29|website=GitLab|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> with some parts later rewritten in [[Go (programming language)|Go]], initially as a source code management solution to collaborate with his team on software development. It later evolved to an integrated solution covering the software development life cycle, and then to the whole DevOps life cycle. The current technology stack includes Go, [[Ruby on Rails]] and [[Vue.js]].\n\nIt follows an [[open-core]] development model where the core functionality is released under an open-source ([[MIT License|MIT]]) license while the additional functionality is under a proprietary license.\n\nGitLab is considered the first Ukrainian [[Unicorn (finance)|unicorn]] valued more than $1 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ain.ua/en/2018/10/30/gitlab-became-a-unicorn |title=GitLab, founded by a Ukrainian citizen, raised $100 million. It became a unicorn valued at $ 1.1 billion|date=2018-10-30|website=AIN.UA|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ain.ua/en/2018/11/30/dmitry-zaporozhets-gitlab |title=Dmitry Zaporozhets, GitLab: \"I believe that GitLab can be called a Ukrainian startup\"|date=2018-11-30|website=AIN.UA|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe product was originally named GitLab and was fully [[free and open-source software]] distributed under the [[MIT License]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenextweb.com/apps/2011/10/13/ship-it-faster-and-cheaper-gitlab-is-github-for-your-own-servers |title=Ship it faster and cheaper - GitLab is GitHub for your own servers - The Next Web|last=Olanoff|first=Drew|date=13 October 2011|work=The Next Web}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://about.gitlab.com/2013/07/22/announcing-gitlab-enterprise-edition |title=GitLab - Announcing GitLab 6.0 Enterprise Edition|work=gitlab.com}}</ref> the product was split into two distinct versions: GitLab CE: Community Edition and GitLab EE: Enterprise Edition. At that time, the license of both remained the same, being both free and open-source software distributed under the [[MIT License]].\n\nIn February 2014, GitLab announced adoption of an [[open-core]] business model.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://about.gitlab.com/2014/02/11/gitlab-ee-license-change |title=GitLab - GitLab Enterprise Edition license change|work=gitlab.com}}</ref> GitLab EE is set under the [[source-available]] proprietary [[EE License]], and contains features not present in the CE version.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://about.gitlab.com/features/#compare|title=GitLab - Features|work=gitlab.com}}</ref> The GitLab CE licensing model remained unchanged and the company continued to develop and support CE edition. While GitLab EE changed to a restricted license, the source-code, issues and merge-requests remained publicly visible.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab-ee|title=GitLab.org / GitLab Enterprise Edition|website=GitLab|language=en|access-date=2018-08-01}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, GitLab acquired [[Gitorious]], a competing [[Git]] hosting service.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://thenextweb.com/insider/2015/03/03/gitlab-acquires-rival-gitorious-will-shut-june-1 |title=Code Collaboration Platform GitLab Acquires Rival Gitorious|last=Degeler|first=Andrii|date=2015-03-03|work=The Next Web|access-date=2018-08-01|language=en-US}}</ref> Gitorious had at the time around 822,000 registered users.<ref name=\":0\"/> Users were encouraged to move to GitLab, and the Gitorious service was discontinued in June 2015.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nIn July 2015, the company raised an additional $1.5 million in [[seed funding]].<ref name=\"raises\">{{cite web|first=Jordan|last=Novet|url=https://venturebeat.com/2015/07/09/y-combinator-backed-github-competitor-gitlab-raises-1-5m |title=Y Combinator-backed GitHub competitor GitLab raises $1.5M|work=VentureBeat}}</ref> Customers as of 2015 included [[Alibaba Group]], [[IBM]], and [[SpaceX]].<ref name=\"raises\"/>\n\nIn September 2015, GitLab raised $4 million in [[Series A round|Series A]] funding from [[Khosla Ventures]].<ref>{{cite web|title = GitLab Raises $4M Series A Round From Khosla Ventures|url = https://techcrunch.com/2015/09/17/gitlab-raises-4m-series-a-round-from-khosla-ventures-for-its-open-source-collaboration-platform|website = TechCrunch|accessdate = 17 Dec 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, the GitLab [[CEO]] confirmed the [[open-core]] business model of the company.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://about.gitlab.com/2016/07/14/building-an-open-source-company-interview-with-gitlabs-ceo |title=Building an Open Source Company: Interview with GitLab's CEO|work=GitLab|access-date=2018-06-06|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, GitLab raised $20 million in Series B funding from [[August Capital]] and others.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/09/13/gitlab-secures-20-million-series-b |title=GitLab secures $20 million Series B|last=Miller|first=Ron|website=TechCrunch|access-date= 3 Nov 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, a database administrator accidentally deleted the production database, in the aftermath of a [[cyber attack]]. Six hours' worth of issue and merge request data was lost.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://about.gitlab.com/2017/02/01/gitlab-dot-com-database-incident|title=GitLab.com Database Incident|access-date= 1 Feb 2017}}</ref> The recovery process was [[live-streamed]] on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLLhSMqmFa5p_QwTyFWnYNDK8LWfvcdoxa|title=Gitlab Database Incident - Live Troubleshooting - YouTube|website=YouTube|language=en|access-date=2018-08-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://thenextweb.com/dd/2017/02/01/gitlab-offline-catastrophic-database-error-loses-mountains-data |title=GitLab offline after catastrophic database error loses mountains of data|last=Hughes|first=Matthew|date=2017-02-01|work=The Next Web|access-date=2018-08-01|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, 2017, GitLab announced the acquisition of [[Gitter]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/03/15/gitlab-acquires-software-chat-startup-gitter-will-open-source-the-code |title=GitLab acquires software chat startup Gitter, will open-source the code|date=2017-03-15|work=VentureBeat|access-date=2018-08-01|language=en-US}}</ref> Included in the announcement was the stated intent that Gitter would continue as a standalone project. Additionally, GitLab announced that the code would become open-source under an [[MIT License]] no later than June 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://about.gitlab.com/2017/03/15/gitter-acquisition |title=Gitter is joining the GitLab team|website=GitLab|access-date=2017-03-15}}</ref>\n\nIn October, 2017, GitLab raised $20 million in Series C funding from [[GV (company)|GV]] and others.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/10/09/gitlab-raises-20m-series-c-round-led-by-gv |title=GitLab raises $20M Series C round led by GV|work=TechCrunch|access-date=2018-08-01|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn January, 2018, GitLab acquired Gemnasium; a service that provided security scanner with alerts for known security vulnerabilities in open-source libraries of various languages.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/01/30/gitlab-acquires-gemnasium-to-strengthen-its-security-services |title=GitLab acquires Gemnasium to strengthen its security services|work=TechCrunch|access-date=2018-08-01|language=en-US}}</ref> The service was scheduled for complete shut-down on May 15. Gemnasium features and technology was integrated into GitLab EE and as part of [[CI/CD]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/gitlab-makes-cicd-tools-available-for-github-repositories |title=GitLab makes CI/CD tools available for GitHub repositories {{!}} ZDNet|last=Condon|first=Stephanie|work=ZDNet|access-date=2018-08-01|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, GitLab announced integration with [[Google Cloud Platform|Google Kubernetes Engine]] (GKE) to simplify the process of spinning up a new cluster to deploy applications.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2018/04/05/gitlab-launches-a-native-integration-with-googles-kubernetes-engine/|title=GitLab gets a native integration with Google\u2019s Kubernetes Engine|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, [[GNOME]] moved to GitLab with over 400 projects and 900 contributors.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://about.gitlab.com/2018/05/31/welcome-gnome-to-gitlab |title=GNOME, welcome to GitLab!|work=GitLab|access-date=2018-06-06|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gnome.org/news/2018/05/gnome-moves-to-gitlab-2 |title=GNOME moves to Gitlab \u2013 GNOME|website=www.gnome.org|language=en|access-date=2018-06-06}}</ref>\n\nGitLab moved from [[Microsoft Azure]] to [[Google Cloud Platform]] in August 11, 2018, which made the service inaccessible to users in Crimea, Cuba, Iran, North Korea, Sudan, and Syria, due to sanctions imposed by [[Office of Foreign Assets Control]] of the United States.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://about.gitlab.com/2018/07/19/gcp-move-update |title=Update on our planned move from Azure to Google Cloud Platform |date=2018-07-19|work=The Official Gitlab Blog|access-date=2018-12-18|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 September 2018, GitLab raised $100 million in Series D-round funding led by ICONIQ Capital.\n\nOn 18 September 2019, GitLab raised $268 million in Series E-round funding led by [[Goldman Sachs]] and Iconiq Capital. For that moment the company was valued at $2.7 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ain.ua/en/2019/09/18/gitlab-raises-268-million |title=Ukrainian startup GitLab raises $268 million at a valuation of $2.7 billion|date=2019-09-18|website=AIN.UA|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/09/17/gitlab-raises-268-million-at-a-2-7-billion-valuation |title=GitLab raises $268 million at a $2.7 billion valuation|date=2019-09-17|website=VentureBeat|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, it was reported that GitLab is expected to reach $100 million in annual recurring revenue in January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2019/12/13/the-newest-members-of-the-100m-arr-club |title=The newest members of the $100M ARR club|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>\n[[File:Gitlab--issue-screen.png|thumb|Issue screen: discussing; markdown supported]]\n\n==Company==\nGitlab Inc. was founded around the pre-existing Gitlab software project.<ref name=inc/> It is a limited liability corporation,<ref name=\"raises\"/> officially launched by Sytse Sijbrandij and Dmitriy Zaporozhets in 2014.<ref name=inc/> \n\nGitLab Inc. is an alumnus of the [[Y Combinator]] [[Startup accelerator|seed accelerator]] programme of its Winter 2015 batch. It raised $1.5 million as seed funding.<ref name=\"raises\"/> In September 2015, GitLab raised $4 million in [[Series A round|Series A]] funding from [[Khosla Ventures]]. It was followed by Series B funding of $20 million by August Capital along with Khosla Ventures in September 2016.<ref name=\":1\"/> In October 2017, [[GV (company)|Google Ventures]] joined the investors leading the Series C funding of $20 million.<ref name=\":2\"/> In September 2018 GitLab raised $100 million in [[Venture round|Series D]] funding led by Iconiq at $1.1 billion valuation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/09/19/gitlab-raises-100-million-from-iconiq-gv-and-khosla-at-1-1-billion-valuation |title=GitLab raises $100 million from Iconiq, GV, and Khosla, at $1.1 billion valuation|date=2018-09-19|work=VentureBeat|access-date=2018-09-20|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nGitlab runs Gitlab.com on a [[freemium]] model; limited access is free to individual developers, but companies pay extra for full access and triple<!--\"200% increase\" would be triple, but I'm not sure one can rely on the journalist having meant that--> the development processing speed.<ref name=inc>{{cite web |last1=Albert-Deitch |first1=Cameron |title=How This Startup Made $10.5 Million in Revenue With Every Single Employee Working From Home |url=https://www.inc.com/cameron-albert-deitch/2018-inc5000-gitlab.html |website=Inc.com |date=13 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nGitLab is a remote-only company, with its headquarters in [[San Francisco]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kamer |first1=Jurriaan |title=No Need to Come to the Office: Making Remote Work at GitLab |url=https://hackernoon.com/no-need-to-come-to-the-office-making-remote-work-at-gitlab-737c42865210 |publisher=Hacker Noon |accessdate=29 November 2018}}</ref> GitLab currently has 1141<ref name=\":3\"/> employees in 56 countries and regions.<ref name=MeetOurTeam/>\n\n==GitLab Application==\n[[File:Gitlab--activity.png|thumb|Activity view; dark theme from external userstyle]]\nGitLab application offers functionality to automate the entire DevOps life cycle from planning to creation, build, verify, security testing, deploying, and monitoring offering high availability and replication, and scalability and available for using [[On-premises software|on-prem]] or [[cloud storage]]. Includes also a [[wiki]], [[Issue tracking system|issue-tracking]] and [[Continuous integration|CI]]/[[Continuous deployment|CD]] pipeline features.\n\nGitLab also offer GitLab Pages product<ref>https://about.gitlab.com/product/pages/</ref><ref>https://www.scivision.dev/gitlab-pages-vs-github-pages/</ref> for creating websites with [[Let's Encrypt]] support since version 12.1.<ref>https://about.gitlab.com/2019/07/22/gitlab-12-1-released/index.html</ref>\n[[File:Gitlab--issue-tracker--dark-theme-from-external-css.png|thumb|Issue tracker; dark theme from external userstyle]]\n\n==Acquisitions==\nIn March 2015, GitLab acquired [[Gitorious]], a free and open-source hosting and on-premise enterprise Git management service provider.\n\nIn March 2017, GitLab acquired [[Gitter]], an [[instant messaging]] platform for developers and announced that it would open-source the Gitter codebase.\n\nIn January 2018, GitLab acquired Gemnasium, a company providing software and services to mitigate security vulnerabilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alejandrocremades/2019/07/21/he-built-a-1-billion-business-where-all-700-employees-work-remotely/|title=He Built A $1 Billion Business Where All 700 Employees Work Remotely|last=Cremades|first=Alejandro|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Comparison of source-code-hosting facilities]]\n* [[Gitea]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|GitLab}}\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Bug tracking systems}}\n\n[[Category:Bug and issue tracking software]]\n[[Category:Build automation]]\n[[Category:Collaborative projects]]\n[[Category:Continuous integration]]<!-- see https://about.gitlab.com/gitlab-ci/ -->\n[[Category:Cross-platform free software]]\n[[Category:Free project management software]]\n[[Category:Free software programmed in Ruby]]\n[[Category:Free version control software]]\n[[Category:Git (software)]]\n[[Category:Go software]]\n[[Category:Open-source software hosting facilities]]\n[[Category:Project hosting websites]]\n[[Category:Software using the MIT license]]\n[[Category:Technology companies of the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Version control]]\n[[Category:Y Combinator companies]]\n[[Category:Remote companies]]\n[[Category:Open-source hosted development tools]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|open-source Git repository host}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Advert|date=June 2018}}\n{{primary sources|date=December 2016}}\n{{More citations needed|date=October 2018}}\n}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name                 = GitLab Inc.\n| logo                 = GitLab logo.svg\n| logo_alt             = GitLab\n| screenshot           = GitLab_running_11.0_(2018-07).png\n| caption              = \n| location             = San Francisco, United States\n| area_served          = [[World]]wide\n| url                  = {{URL|https://gitlab.com}}\n| commercial           = Yes\n| type                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Git]]-repository hosting service\n* Collaborative revision control}}\n| registration         = Optional\n| language             = [[English language|English]]\n| owner                = GitLab Inc.\n| author               = \n| alexa                = {{Decrease}} 2,085 ({{as of|2019|10|27|alt=October 2019}})<ref>{{cite web\n | url        = https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/gitlab.com\n | title      = GitLab.com Alexa Ranking\n | publisher  = Alexa Internet\n | accessdate = 27 October 2019}}</ref>\n| founder              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Sid Sijbrandij]]\n* [[Dmitriy Zaporozhets]]}}\n| key_people           = {{Plainlist|\n* Sid Sijbrandij ([[CEO]])\n* Dmitriy Zaporozhets ([[Chief technology officer|CTO]])}}\n| num_users            = \n| num_employees        = 1,268<ref name=MeetOurTeam>{{cite web\n | url         = https://about.gitlab.com/team\n | title       = GitLab Team\n | access-date = 25 April 2020}}</ref>\n| industry             = [[Software]]\n| programming_language = [[Ruby (programming language)|Ruby]],<ref name=\"Flowers\"/> [[Go (programming language)|Go]], and [[Vue.js]]\n| launch_date          = {{Start date and age|2011}}\n| current_status       = Online\n}}\n\n{{Infobox software\n| name                   = GitLab Application\n| bodystyle              = width:300px\n| screenshot             = \n| caption                = \n| latest release version = 12.10.1\n| latest release date    = {{Start date and age|2020|04|24}}<ref name=\"v12-10-1\">{{cite web\n | url        = https://about.gitlab.com/releases/2020/04/24/gitlab-12-10-1-released/\n | title      = GitLab Patch Release: 12.10.1\n | author     = Robert Speicher\n | publisher  = GitLab\n | date       = 24 April 2020\n | accessdate = 25 April 2020}}</ref>\n| operating system       = [[Cross-platform]]\n| platform               = [[x86-64]], [[ARMhf]]\n| license                = '''Community Edition:''' [[MIT License]] and other free software licenses<ref name=\"ce-license\" /><br>'''Enterprise Edition:''' [[Source-available]] [[proprietary software]]<ref name=\"ce-license\">{{cite web\n | url   = https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/blob/master/LICENSE\n | title = GitLab LICENSE file\n | accessdate = 29 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | url   = https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/blob/master/ee/LICENSE\n | title = GitLab Enterprise Edition LICENSE file\n | accessdate = 29 March 2020}}</ref>\n| programming language   = [[Ruby (programming language)|Ruby]]\n}}\n\n'''GitLab''' is a [[web-based]] [[DevOps]] lifecycle tool that provides a [[Git]]-[[repository (version control)|repository]] manager providing [[wiki]], [[Issue tracking system|issue-tracking]] and [[continuous integration]]/[[continuous deployment]] pipeline<ref name=\":3\">https://about.gitlab.com/features/gitlab-ci-cd/</ref> features, using an [[Open-source software|open-source]] license, developed by GitLab Inc. The software was created by [[Ukrainians]] Dmitriy Zaporozhets and Valery Sizov,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://about.gitlab.com/company/history |title=History of GitLab|website=GitLab|language=en|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref> and is used by several large tech companies including [[Juniper]], [[Cisco]], [[IBM]], [[Sony]], [[J\u00fclich Research Center]], [[NASA]], [[Alibaba]], [[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]], [[Invincea]], [[O'Reilly Media]], [[Leibniz-Rechenzentrum]] (LRZ), [[CERN]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenextweb.com/insider/2014/06/04/github-rival-gitlab-building-business-just-0-1-paying-customers |title=GitLab is building a business with 0.1% of paying customers|last=Degeler|first=Andrii|date=4 June 2014|work=The Next Web}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://information-technology.web.cern.ch/services/cern-commercial|title=Services - CERN or commercial provider?|author=CERN|work=cern.ch}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lrz.de/services/netzdienste/gitlab_en |title=Services - GitLab}}</ref> [[European XFEL]], [[GNOME Foundation]], [[Boeing]], [[Autodata]], [[Nvidia|NVIDIA]], and [[SpaceX]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://venturebeat.com/2015/07/09/y-combinator-backed-github-competitor-gitlab-raises-1-5m |title=Y Combinator-backed GitHub competitor GitLab raises $1.5M|date=2015-07-09|work=VentureBeat|access-date=2018-06-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe code was originally written in [[Ruby (programming language)|Ruby]],<ref name=\"Flowers\">{{cite web|url=https://about.gitlab.com/2018/10/29/why-we-use-rails-to-build-gitlab |title=Why we use Ruby on Rails to build GitLab|last=Flowers|first=Aricka|date=2018-10-29|website=GitLab|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> with some parts later rewritten in [[Go (programming language)|Go]], initially as a source code management solution to collaborate with his team on software development. It later evolved to an integrated solution covering the software development life cycle, and then to the whole DevOps life cycle. The current technology stack includes Go, [[Ruby on Rails]] and [[Vue.js]].\n\nIt follows an [[open-core]] development model where the core functionality is released under an open-source ([[MIT License|MIT]]) license while the additional functionality is under a proprietary license.\n\nGitLab is considered the first Ukrainian [[Unicorn (finance)|unicorn]] valued more than $1 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ain.ua/en/2018/10/30/gitlab-became-a-unicorn |title=GitLab, founded by a Ukrainian citizen, raised $100 million. It became a unicorn valued at $ 1.1 billion|date=2018-10-30|website=AIN.UA|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ain.ua/en/2018/11/30/dmitry-zaporozhets-gitlab |title=Dmitry Zaporozhets, GitLab: \"I believe that GitLab can be called a Ukrainian startup\"|date=2018-11-30|website=AIN.UA|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe product was originally named GitLab and was fully [[free and open-source software]] distributed under the [[MIT License]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenextweb.com/apps/2011/10/13/ship-it-faster-and-cheaper-gitlab-is-github-for-your-own-servers |title=Ship it faster and cheaper - GitLab is GitHub for your own servers - The Next Web|last=Olanoff|first=Drew|date=13 October 2011|work=The Next Web}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://about.gitlab.com/2013/07/22/announcing-gitlab-enterprise-edition |title=GitLab - Announcing GitLab 6.0 Enterprise Edition|work=gitlab.com}}</ref> the product was split into two distinct versions: GitLab CE: Community Edition and GitLab EE: Enterprise Edition. At that time, the license of both remained the same, being both free and open-source software distributed under the [[MIT License]].\n\nIn February 2014, GitLab announced adoption of an [[open-core]] business model.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://about.gitlab.com/2014/02/11/gitlab-ee-license-change |title=GitLab - GitLab Enterprise Edition license change|work=gitlab.com}}</ref> GitLab EE is set under the [[source-available]] proprietary [[EE License]], and contains features not present in the CE version.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://about.gitlab.com/features/#compare|title=GitLab - Features|work=gitlab.com}}</ref> The GitLab CE licensing model remained unchanged and the company continued to develop and support CE edition. While GitLab EE changed to a restricted license, the source-code, issues and merge-requests remained publicly visible.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab-ee|title=GitLab.org / GitLab Enterprise Edition|website=GitLab|language=en|access-date=2018-08-01}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, GitLab acquired [[Gitorious]], a competing [[Git]] hosting service.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://thenextweb.com/insider/2015/03/03/gitlab-acquires-rival-gitorious-will-shut-june-1 |title=Code Collaboration Platform GitLab Acquires Rival Gitorious|last=Degeler|first=Andrii|date=2015-03-03|work=The Next Web|access-date=2018-08-01|language=en-US}}</ref> Gitorious had at the time around 822,000 registered users.<ref name=\":0\"/> Users were encouraged to move to GitLab, and the Gitorious service was discontinued in June 2015.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nIn July 2015, the company raised an additional $1.5 million in [[seed funding]].<ref name=\"raises\">{{cite web|first=Jordan|last=Novet|url=https://venturebeat.com/2015/07/09/y-combinator-backed-github-competitor-gitlab-raises-1-5m |title=Y Combinator-backed GitHub competitor GitLab raises $1.5M|work=VentureBeat}}</ref> Customers as of 2015 included [[Alibaba Group]], [[IBM]], and [[SpaceX]].<ref name=\"raises\"/>\n\nIn September 2015, GitLab raised $4 million in [[Series A round|Series A]] funding from [[Khosla Ventures]].<ref>{{cite web|title = GitLab Raises $4M Series A Round From Khosla Ventures|url = https://techcrunch.com/2015/09/17/gitlab-raises-4m-series-a-round-from-khosla-ventures-for-its-open-source-collaboration-platform|website = TechCrunch|accessdate = 17 Dec 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, the GitLab [[CEO]] confirmed the [[open-core]] business model of the company.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://about.gitlab.com/2016/07/14/building-an-open-source-company-interview-with-gitlabs-ceo |title=Building an Open Source Company: Interview with GitLab's CEO|work=GitLab|access-date=2018-06-06|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, GitLab raised $20 million in Series B funding from [[August Capital]] and others.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/09/13/gitlab-secures-20-million-series-b |title=GitLab secures $20 million Series B|last=Miller|first=Ron|website=TechCrunch|access-date= 3 Nov 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, a database administrator accidentally deleted the production database, in the aftermath of a [[cyber attack]]. Six hours' worth of issue and merge request data was lost.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://about.gitlab.com/2017/02/01/gitlab-dot-com-database-incident|title=GitLab.com Database Incident|access-date= 1 Feb 2017}}</ref> The recovery process was [[live-streamed]] on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLLhSMqmFa5p_QwTyFWnYNDK8LWfvcdoxa|title=Gitlab Database Incident - Live Troubleshooting - YouTube|website=YouTube|language=en|access-date=2018-08-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://thenextweb.com/dd/2017/02/01/gitlab-offline-catastrophic-database-error-loses-mountains-data |title=GitLab offline after catastrophic database error loses mountains of data|last=Hughes|first=Matthew|date=2017-02-01|work=The Next Web|access-date=2018-08-01|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, 2017, GitLab announced the acquisition of [[Gitter]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/03/15/gitlab-acquires-software-chat-startup-gitter-will-open-source-the-code |title=GitLab acquires software chat startup Gitter, will open-source the code|date=2017-03-15|work=VentureBeat|access-date=2018-08-01|language=en-US}}</ref> Included in the announcement was the stated intent that Gitter would continue as a standalone project. Additionally, GitLab announced that the code would become open-source under an [[MIT License]] no later than June 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://about.gitlab.com/2017/03/15/gitter-acquisition |title=Gitter is joining the GitLab team|website=GitLab|access-date=2017-03-15}}</ref>\n\nIn October, 2017, GitLab raised $20 million in Series C funding from [[GV (company)|GV]] and others.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/10/09/gitlab-raises-20m-series-c-round-led-by-gv |title=GitLab raises $20M Series C round led by GV|work=TechCrunch|access-date=2018-08-01|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn January, 2018, GitLab acquired Gemnasium; a service that provided security scanner with alerts for known security vulnerabilities in open-source libraries of various languages.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/01/30/gitlab-acquires-gemnasium-to-strengthen-its-security-services |title=GitLab acquires Gemnasium to strengthen its security services|work=TechCrunch|access-date=2018-08-01|language=en-US}}</ref> The service was scheduled for complete shut-down on May 15. Gemnasium features and technology was integrated into GitLab EE and as part of [[CI/CD]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/gitlab-makes-cicd-tools-available-for-github-repositories |title=GitLab makes CI/CD tools available for GitHub repositories {{!}} ZDNet|last=Condon|first=Stephanie|work=ZDNet|access-date=2018-08-01|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, GitLab announced integration with [[Google Cloud Platform|Google Kubernetes Engine]] (GKE) to simplify the process of spinning up a new cluster to deploy applications.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2018/04/05/gitlab-launches-a-native-integration-with-googles-kubernetes-engine/|title=GitLab gets a native integration with Google\u2019s Kubernetes Engine|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, [[GNOME]] moved to GitLab with over 400 projects and 900 contributors.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://about.gitlab.com/2018/05/31/welcome-gnome-to-gitlab |title=GNOME, welcome to GitLab!|work=GitLab|access-date=2018-06-06|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gnome.org/news/2018/05/gnome-moves-to-gitlab-2 |title=GNOME moves to Gitlab \u2013 GNOME|website=www.gnome.org|language=en|access-date=2018-06-06}}</ref>\n\nGitLab moved from [[Microsoft Azure]] to [[Google Cloud Platform]] in August 11, 2018, which made the service inaccessible to users in Crimea, Cuba, Iran, North Korea, Sudan, and Syria, due to sanctions imposed by [[Office of Foreign Assets Control]] of the United States.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://about.gitlab.com/2018/07/19/gcp-move-update |title=Update on our planned move from Azure to Google Cloud Platform |date=2018-07-19|work=The Official Gitlab Blog|access-date=2018-12-18|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 September 2018, GitLab raised $100 million in Series D-round funding led by ICONIQ Capital.\n\nOn 18 September 2019, GitLab raised $268 million in Series E-round funding led by [[Goldman Sachs]] and Iconiq Capital. For that moment the company was valued at $2.7 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ain.ua/en/2019/09/18/gitlab-raises-268-million |title=Ukrainian startup GitLab raises $268 million at a valuation of $2.7 billion|date=2019-09-18|website=AIN.UA|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/09/17/gitlab-raises-268-million-at-a-2-7-billion-valuation |title=GitLab raises $268 million at a $2.7 billion valuation|date=2019-09-17|website=VentureBeat|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, it was reported that GitLab is expected to reach $100 million in annual recurring revenue in January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2019/12/13/the-newest-members-of-the-100m-arr-club |title=The newest members of the $100M ARR club|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>\n[[File:Gitlab--issue-screen.png|thumb|Issue screen: discussing; markdown supported]]\n\n==Company==\nGitlab Inc. was founded around the pre-existing Gitlab software project.<ref name=inc/> It is a limited liability corporation,<ref name=\"raises\"/> officially launched by Sytse Sijbrandij and Dmitriy Zaporozhets in 2014.<ref name=inc/> \n\nGitLab Inc. is an alumnus of the [[Y Combinator]] [[Startup accelerator|seed accelerator]] programme of its Winter 2015 batch. It raised $1.5 million as seed funding.<ref name=\"raises\"/> In September 2015, GitLab raised $4 million in [[Series A round|Series A]] funding from [[Khosla Ventures]]. It was followed by Series B funding of $20 million by August Capital along with Khosla Ventures in September 2016.<ref name=\":1\"/> In October 2017, [[GV (company)|Google Ventures]] joined the investors leading the Series C funding of $20 million.<ref name=\":2\"/> In September 2018 GitLab raised $100 million in [[Venture round|Series D]] funding led by Iconiq at $1.1 billion valuation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/09/19/gitlab-raises-100-million-from-iconiq-gv-and-khosla-at-1-1-billion-valuation |title=GitLab raises $100 million from Iconiq, GV, and Khosla, at $1.1 billion valuation|date=2018-09-19|work=VentureBeat|access-date=2018-09-20|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nGitlab runs Gitlab.com on a [[freemium]] model; limited access is free to individual developers, but companies pay extra for full access and triple<!--\"200% increase\" would be triple, but I'm not sure one can rely on the journalist having meant that--> the development processing speed.<ref name=inc>{{cite web |last1=Albert-Deitch |first1=Cameron |title=How This Startup Made $10.5 Million in Revenue With Every Single Employee Working From Home |url=https://www.inc.com/cameron-albert-deitch/2018-inc5000-gitlab.html |website=Inc.com |date=13 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nGitLab is a remote-only company, with its headquarters in [[San Francisco]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kamer |first1=Jurriaan |title=No Need to Come to the Office: Making Remote Work at GitLab |url=https://hackernoon.com/no-need-to-come-to-the-office-making-remote-work-at-gitlab-737c42865210 |publisher=Hacker Noon |accessdate=29 November 2018}}</ref> GitLab currently has 1141<ref name=\":3\"/> employees in 56 countries and regions.<ref name=MeetOurTeam/>\n\n==GitLab Application==\n[[File:Gitlab--activity.png|thumb|Activity view; dark theme from external userstyle]]\nGitLab application offers functionality to automate the entire DevOps life cycle from planning to creation, build, verify, security testing, deploying, and monitoring offering high availability and replication, and scalability and available for using [[On-premises software|on-prem]] or [[cloud storage]]. Includes also a [[wiki]], [[Issue tracking system|issue-tracking]] and [[Continuous integration|CI]]/[[Continuous deployment|CD]] pipeline features.\n\nGitLab also offer GitLab Pages product<ref>https://about.gitlab.com/product/pages/</ref><ref>https://www.scivision.dev/gitlab-pages-vs-github-pages/</ref> for creating websites with [[Let's Encrypt]] support since version 12.1.<ref>https://about.gitlab.com/2019/07/22/gitlab-12-1-released/index.html</ref>\n[[File:Gitlab--issue-tracker--dark-theme-from-external-css.png|thumb|Issue tracker; dark theme from external userstyle]]\n\n==Acquisitions==\nIn March 2015, GitLab acquired [[Gitorious]], a free and open-source hosting and on-premise enterprise Git management service provider.\n\nIn March 2017, GitLab acquired [[Gitter]], an [[instant messaging]] platform for developers and announced that it would open-source the Gitter codebase.\n\nIn January 2018, GitLab acquired Gemnasium, a company providing software and services to mitigate security vulnerabilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alejandrocremades/2019/07/21/he-built-a-1-billion-business-where-all-700-employees-work-remotely/|title=He Built A $1 Billion Business Where All 700 Employees Work Remotely|last=Cremades|first=Alejandro|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Comparison of source-code-hosting facilities]]\n* [[Gitea]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|GitLab}}\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Bug tracking systems}}\n\n[[Category:Bug and issue tracking software]]\n[[Category:Build automation]]\n[[Category:Collaborative projects]]\n[[Category:Continuous integration]]<!-- see https://about.gitlab.com/gitlab-ci/ -->\n[[Category:Cross-platform free software]]\n[[Category:Free project management software]]\n[[Category:Free software programmed in Ruby]]\n[[Category:Free version control software]]\n[[Category:Git (software)]]\n[[Category:Go software]]\n[[Category:Open-source software hosting facilities]]\n[[Category:Project hosting websites]]\n[[Category:Software using the MIT license]]\n[[Category:Technology companies of the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Version control]]\n[[Category:Y Combinator companies]]\n[[Category:Remote companies]]\n[[Category:Open-source hosted development tools]]\n", "name_user": "Herakleitoszefesu", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GitLab"}
{"title_page": "Amaravati", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date = November 2019}}\n{{Distinguish|Amravati, Maharashtra|Amarawati}}\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name                   = Amaravati\n| other_name                      = Dhanyakatakam\n| settlement_type                 = [[Historical]] [[City]] of [[Andhra Pradesh]]\n| image_skyline                   = {{photomontage\n|photo1a = BrMus Amravati.jpg\n|photo2a = Amaravati Stupa Model.jpg\n|photo2b = British Museum Asia 14.jpg\n|photo3b = Amaravati Buddha Statue Real.png\n|photo4a = Main Structure of Amareswara Temple.jpg\n|photo4b = Chakra at amaravati.jpg\n|photo5a = Amaravati Stupa in AP W IMG 8075.jpg\n|photo6a = Amaravati 1.jpg\n|photo6b = Discription plate, Amaravati stupa. at Amaravati. A (12).JPG\n|photo7a = High Court of Andhra Pradesh, Amaravati (May 2019) 1.jpg\n|spacing = 1\n|color = white\n|size = 280\n}}\n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = Clockwise from top : [[Amaravati Marbles]] at [[British Museum]], [[Amaravati Stupa|Mahachaitya]] - lost Amaravati Stupa at Chennai Museum, Details of [[Amaravati Stupa|Mahachaitya]], [[Dhyana Buddha statue|Gautam Buddha Statue]] at [[Amaravati]], [[Amaralingeswara Temple]]; Buddha Chakra sculpture, [[Amaravati Stupa]], [[Andhra Pradesh High Court]]; .\n| nickname                        = '''Heritage City of Andhra Pradesh''' '''Historical City of Andhra Pradesh''' \n| image_map                       = \n| map_alt                         = A map showing location of Amaravati in Andhra Pradesh, India.\n| map_caption                     = Location of Amaravati in Andhra Pradesh, India\n| pushpin_map                     = India Andhra Pradesh#India\n| pushpin_label_position          = right\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|16.541|N|80.515|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flagicon|India}} [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = {{flagicon image|Andhraseal.png}} [[Andhra Pradesh]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of regions of India|Region]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Coromandel Coast|Coromandel]]\n| subdivision_type3               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name3               = [[Guntur district|Guntur]]\n| established_date                = 1 September 2014 <ref>http://ccdmc.co.in/downloads/Amaravati-concept-handbook_modified.pdf</ref>\n| government_type                 = Planning agencies\n| governing_body                  = [[Andhra Pradesh Capital Region Development Authority|APCRDA]]\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = <ref name=\"apcrda\">{{cite web|title=Declaration of A.P. Capital City Area\u2013Revised orders|url=https://crda.ap.gov.in/APCRDADOCS/GOSACTSRULES/CRDA/01~14142015MAUD_MS141.PDF|website=Andhra Nation|publisher=Municipal Administration and Urban Development Department|accessdate=21 February 2016|date=22 September 2015}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2                  = 217.23\n| area_metro_footnotes            = <ref name=\"metro\">{{cite news|last1=Subba Rao|first1=GVR|title=Capital region expands as CRDA redraws boundaries|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Vijayawada/capital-region-expands-as-crda-redraws-boundaries/article7680051.ece|accessdate=31 October 2015|work=The Hindu|date=23 September 2015|location=Vijayawada}}</ref>{{refn|The Amaravati metropolitan area also includes portions of [[Amaravathi, Guntur district|Amaravathi]], [[Guntur]], [[Vijayawada]], [[Tenali]], [[Gudivada Municipality|Gudivada]], [[Tadepalle Municipality|Tadepalle]], [[Jaggayyapeta]], [[Mangalagiri Municipality|Mangalagiri]], [[Mopidevi]], [[Nuzvid]], [[Ponnur Municipality|Ponnur]], [[Sattenapalle]], [[Challapalle]], [[Nandigama]], [[Ghantasala, Krishna district|Ghantasala]],  [[Vuyyuru]] adjoining the [[Andhra Pradesh Capital Region|APCR]].|group=upper-alpha}}\n| area_metro_km2                  = 8352.69\n| population_total                = 103000\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_footnotes            = <ref>{{cite news|title=CRDA eyes CSR funds to push job potential in capital city|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/vijayawada/CRDA-eyes-CSR-funds-to-push-job-potential-in-capital-city/articleshow/47891827.cms|accessdate=18 August 2015|work=The Times of India|date=1 July 2015|location=Guntur}}</ref>\n| population_metro                = 5800000\n| population_metro_footnotes      = <ref>{{cite news|title=Amaravati to be divided into eight urban plan areas|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/new-capital-region-to-be-divided-into-eight-urban-plan-areas/article7063043.ece|accessdate=21 June 2016|work=The Hindu|date=3 April 2015}}</ref>\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|Pincode(s)]]\n| postal_code                     = 520 XXX, 521 XXX, 522 XXX\n| area_code                       = \n| registration_plate              = AP-7, AP-8, AP-39<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aptransport.org/html/registration-districtcodes.html|title=Registration District Codes|publisher=Andhra Pradesh Transport Department|date=2019-12-06|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>\n| blank2_name                     = {{nowrap|Official languages}}\n| blank2_info                     = [[Telugu language|Telugu]]\n| website                         = {{URL|https://crda.ap.gov.in/|Amaravati official website}}\n| footnotes                       = {{Reflist|group=upper-alpha}}\n| name                            = \n| founder                         = [[N. Chandrababu Naidu]]\n| established_title1              = [[Municipal incorporation|Established]]\n| established_date1               = 22 October 2015\n| named_for                       = Amareshwara swamy\n| established_title               = Mission\n}}\n'''Amaravati''' ([[List of renamed places in India|formerly]] '''Dh\u0101nyakatakam''') is the most important [[heritage]], [[Buddhist texts|holy buddhist]] and [[Historical cities|historical city]] of [[Andhra Pradesh]]. It's history dates back to 2nd Century BCE when it was the [[capital]] of [[Satavahana dynasty|Satavahana Dynasty]] ([[Andhras]]), one of the earliest greatest kings of [[India]] and the [[Ancestor|ancestral]] [[dynasty]] of [[Andhra Pradesh]]. [[Satavahana dynasty|Satavahanas]] are most respected and viewed as very prominent and greatest rulers in [[Andhra Pradesh]] [[History of Andhra Pradesh|history]] as they were the reason for the origin of [[Telugu New Year]], [[Ugadi]] from this region. Their language was [[Prakrit]] of [[Brahmi script|Brahmi Script]], which served as the base for the [[script]] of [[Telugu language|Telugu Language]]. They issued many [[Gautamiputra Satakarni|coins]] with this [[Prakrit]] language which can be found in many insciptions in this region today. They even started the [[Shaka Calendar|Satavahana Calendar]], The first Indian National Calendar from this region. They even respected and practised [[Buddhism]] and partly responsible for the prevalence of [[Buddhism]] in the region.   \n\nThe city was also once the [[Holy place|holy site]] of [[Mahayana Buddhism]]. The city used to have a biggest [[Stupa|Buddhist Stupa]] known as [[Amaravati Stupa|Mahachaitya]] (also known as [[Amaravati Stupa]]) which was detroyed over the time. It was also the center of [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] [[Culture of Buddhism|learning]] and [[Buddhist art|art]] where many [[Bhikkhu|buddhist followers]] from many [[Southeast Asia|South East Asian]] countries used to visit and practice the [[Culture of Buddhism|buddhist culture]] here in this place. It can be seen from the [[Amaravati Stupa]], many [[Inscriptions|Buddhist inscriptions]], [[Sculpture|sculptures]] and [[Dhyana Buddha statue|Gautam Buddha Statue]] in the city. Many other ancient [[Amaravati Marbles|Amaravati Buddhist Marbels]] and Buddhist [[remains]] from the region were unfortunately destroyed over the time and some of them were exported to Chennai Museum and [[British Museum]] during the [[British Raj|British rule]] which can be seen there today. The sculptures on the [[Amaravati Marbles|Limestone Marbels]] depict many [[Buddhist art]], [[Epigraphy|incriptions]] and [[Amaravati Stupa|buddhist stupas]] serving as an eye feast. The city along with [[Nagarjunakonda|Nagarjuna Konda]] is viewed as one of the richest [[Holy place|holy sites]] of [[Buddhism]] in the entire [[India]] and [[Andhra Pradesh]].  \n\nIt is also [[capital city|state capital]] of the Indian state of [[Andhra Pradesh]], and the primary city of the state's [[Andhra Pradesh Capital Region|Capital Region]]. Built on allotted space on the southern banks of [[Krishna River]] in [[Guntur district]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://crda.ap.gov.in/APCRDADOCS/GOSACTSRULES/Capital%20City/01~131223042015MAUD_MS97.PDF|title=Naming of the Residuary Andhra Pradesh State Capital as \"AMARAVATI\"|date=23 April 2015|website=Andhra Nation|publisher=Municipal Administration and Urban Development Department|accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> selected close to the geographical center of the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/pt/650051486971245674/pdf/Environmental-and-Social-Management-Framework.pdf|title=Overview of the Capital City and Geographical location of Amaravati|date=August 2017|website=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Akbar|first1=Syed|title=Amaravati as official capital will boost Andhra Pradesh's image|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/visakhapatnam/Amaravati-as-official-capital-will-boost-Andhra-Pradeshs-image/articleshow/53595008.cms|accessdate=1 May 2017|work=The Times of India|date=8 Aug 2016}}</ref> Amaravati is a recently constructed [[planned city]]. The city was constructed to serve as Andhra Pradesh's new capital after [[Telangana]] was split off as a separate state in 2014. The former Andhraite capital, [[Hyderabad]], is now the capital of Telangana. \n\nIn response, Amaravati was founded by [[N. Chandrababu Naidu]] in the same year 2014 as the [[Greenfield land|Greenfield administrative capital city]] of the Andhra Pradesh state, and its [[cornerstone|foundation stone]] was laid at [[Uddandarayunipalem]] by the [[Prime Minister of India]] [[Narendra Modi]] on 22 October 2015.<ref name=\"foundation\">{{citation|title=Thousands descend on Andhra village Uddandarayunipalem to watch history in making|date=22 October 2015|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/thousands-descend-on-andhra-village-uddandarayunipalem-to-watch-history-in-making/articleshow/49491280.cms|newspaper=The Economic Times}}</ref> The city is built on {{convert|217|sqkm}} of [[riverfront]] designed to have 51% green space and 10% of water bodies.<ref name=\"apcrda\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/fpmYw43wSuaTHwfTgTlpgK/Amaravati-A-capital-idea.html|title=Amaravati: A capital idea, but how feasible?}}</ref> \n\nAs of October 2016, the majority of departments and officials of the Andhra Pradesh State Government are operating from the interim [[Andhra Pradesh Secretariat]] facilities located in the [[Velagapudi]] area of Amaravati, with only a skeleton staff remaining behind in Hyderabad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-andhra-pradesh-secretariat-starts-functioning-from-interim-government-complex-at-amaravati-2260970|title=Andhra Pradesh Secretariat starts functioning from interim government complex at Amaravati  & Updates at Daily News & Analysis|date=3 October 2016}}</ref> From April 2016, the office of the [[Chief Minister of Andhra Pradesh]] has operated from Velagapudi. The [[Andhra Pradesh Legislature]] remained in Hyderabad until March 2017, when it relocated to newly constructed interim legislative buildings in Velagapudi.<ref>[https://www.news18.com/news/india/andhra-pradesh-holds-maiden-budget-session-in-new-capital-amaravati-1356763.html Andhra Pradesh Holds Maiden Budget Session in New Capital Amaravati]</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe name \"Amaravati\" derives from the historical [[Amaravathi (village), Andhra Pradesh|Amaravathi village]], the ancient capital of the [[Satavahana dynasty]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/After-18-centuries-Amaravati-set-to-become-a-capital-again/articleshow/49489009.cms|title=After 18 centuries, Amaravati set to become a 'capital' again|date=22 October 2015|newspaper=The Times of India}}</ref>  The metropolitan areas of [[Guntur]], [[Vijayawada]] and [[Tenali]] are the major [[conurbation]]s of Amaravati.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/explained/why-amaravati-has-been-chosen-as-the-new-andhra-pradesh-capital/|title=Explained: Why Amaravati has been chosen as the new Andhra Pradesh capital|date=21 October 2015|work=The Indian Express}}</ref>\n\n''Amaravati'' translates literally as 'the place for immortals'.  It was formerly named after ''Dhanyakataka'', the location where Shakyamuni Buddha taught the Heart Essence form of the Kalachakra Dharma to the Shambala kings.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n== History ==\n[[File: Southern India, Andhra Pradesh, Amaravati, Satavahana Period - Veneration of the Buddha as a Fiery Piller - 1943.72 - Cleveland Museum of Art.tif|alt=Southern India, Andhra Pradesh, Amaravati, Satavahana Period \u2013 Veneration of the Buddha as a Fiery Piller \u2013 1943.72 \u2013 Cleveland Museum of Art|thumb|Southern India, Andhra Pradesh, Amaravati, Satavahana Period \u2013 Veneration of the Buddha as a Fiery Piller -100 BC \u2013 c. AD 200 \u2013 Cleveland Museum of Art, Ohio, United States|left]]\nThe present capital area has its historical significance of having recorded its first-ever legislation 2,200 years ago.<ref>{{cite news|title=After 2,200 years, Amaravati gets back its legislation power|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/amaravati/after-2200-years-amaravati-gets-back-its-legislation-power/articleshow/57505968.cms|accessdate=1 May 2017|work=The Times of India}}</ref> The present-day capital region includes the [[Amaravathi (village), Andhra Pradesh|ancient Amaravati]]. The area has been ruled by the [[Mauryas]], [[Satavahanas]], [[Andhra Ikshvaku|Ikshvakus]], [[Vishnukundina]], [[Pallavas]], [[Cholas]], [[Kakatiyas]], [[Delhi Sultanate]], [[Musunuri Nayaks]], [[Bahmani Sultanate]], [[Vijayanagara Empire]], Sultanate of [[Golconda]] and [[Mughal Empire]] successively before the founding of the [[Nizam of Hyderabad]] in 1724. It was ceded to [[Kingdom of France|France]] in 1750 but was captured by [[Kingdom of Great Britain|the British]] in 1759. Guntur returned to the Nizamate in 1768 but was ceded to Britain again in 1788. It was briefly occupied by [[Hyder Ali]]. It was then ruled by [[Vasireddy Venkatadri Nayudu]]. It was part of [[Madras Presidency]] during the British colonial period.\n\nAs per the [[Andhra Pradesh Reorganisation Act, 2014]], [[Hyderabad]] became the capital of the then newly formed state of [[Telangana]], post bifurcation of [[Andhra Pradesh]]. However, Hyderabad would remain as the joint capital of both states for a period not exceeding ten years. Hence, Amaravati is being built to serve as the capital of Andhra Pradesh.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Andhra Pradesh Reorganisation Act, 2014 |url=http://reorganisation.ap.gov.in/downloads/A.P.RegulationAct2014.pdf|website=AP Reorganisation Portal|publisher=The Gazette of India Extraordinary|accessdate=9 February 2015 |location=New Delhi|date=1 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe foundation for the city was laid at [[Uddandarayunipalem]] on 22 October 2015. The [[Prime Minister of India]], [[Narendra Modi]];  the  [[Chief Minister of Andhra Pradesh]], [[Nara Chandrababu Naidu]]; the [[Vice President of India]] and the Chairman of the Rajya Sabha [[Muppavarapu Venkaiah Naidu]]; then Governor [[E. S. L. Narasimhan]]; the [[Japan]]ese minister for economy trade and industry, [[Yosuke Takagi]]; and the [[Ministry of Trade and Industry (Singapore)|Singaporean Minister for Trade and Industry]], [[S. Iswaran]], laid the foundation for the city.<ref name=\"foundation\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/506499/andhra-cm-scales-down-amaravathi.html|title=Andhra CM scales down Amaravati foundation fete}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nThe city is being built in [[Guntur district]], on the banks of the [[Krishna River]]. The city will be {{convert|40|km}} south-west of [[Vijayawada]], {{convert|32|km}} north of [[Guntur]], {{convert|70|km}} south-east of [[Tenali]] surrounding the [[Coromandel Coast]] of [[Coastal Andhra|Coastal Andhra region]] in [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[India]].<ref>{{cite news|author1=U Sudhakar Reddy|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/141031/nation-current-affairs/article/andhra-pradesh-capital-come-riverfront-guntur-district|title=Andhra Pradesh capital to come up on riverfront in Guntur district|date=31 October 2014|work=Deccan Chronicle|accessdate=1 November 2014|location=Hyderabad}}</ref>\n\n== Vision ==\n[[File:Amaravathi 3D print.jpg|thumb|Amaravati 3D Sketch Map at [[APCRDA]] Office.|alt=|left]]\n\nThe 13th Chief Minister of Andhra Pradesh [[N. Chandrababu Naidu]] envisioned Amaravati to be the people-centric pioneer [[Smart City]] of India, built around sustainability and livability principles, and to be the happiest city in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/amaravati-will-be-developed-as-the-happiest-city-in-the-world-andhra-cm/article23492961.ece|title=Amaravati will be developed as the happiest city in the world: Andhra CM|first=Ch R. S.|last=Sarma|website=@businessline}}</ref> Among the innovative features on the drawing board are navigation canals<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/vijayawada/Civil-works-of-administrative-city-to-start-by-november-1-CM/articleshow/55083133.cms|title=Civil works of administrative city to start by November 1: CM|website=The Times of India}}</ref> around the city, and connecting to an island in the Krishna River. The Government has envisaged an investment needed<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/andhras-bonds-for-amaravati-oversubscribed-by-1-5-times/articleshow/65501684.cms|title=Andhra\u2019s bonds for Amaravati oversubscribed by 1.5 times|first=C. R.|last=Sukumar|date=22 August 2018|via=The Economic Times}}</ref> of {{USD|2\u20134 billion}} for the development of the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/amaravati-development-needs-2-4-billion-investment-chandrababu-naidu/articleshow/65562480.cms|title=Amaravati development needs $2\u20134 billion investment: Chandrababu Naidu|date=27 August 2018|via=The Economic Times}}</ref> \n\nThe city is being designed to have 51% [[Urban open space|green space]] and 10% of water bodies, with a plan to house some of the most iconic buildings there. It is being modeled on Singapore, with the master plan being prepared by two Singapore government-appointed consultants. Other international consultants and architects will then be brought in to give the city an international flavor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/how-andhra-pradesh-plans-to-make-its-new-capital-amaravati-a-world-class-city/articleshow/58767503.cms|title=How Andhra Pradesh plans to make its new capital Amaravati a world-class city|first=Shantanu Nandan|last=Sharma|date=21 May 2017|via=The Economic Times}}</ref>\n\n== City Planning ==\n[[File:3D Model of Amaravati in APCRDA office, Vijayawada (6).jpg|thumb|3D Model of Amaravati in APCRDA office,]]\n[[File:3D Model of Amaravati in APCRDA office, Vijayawada (4).jpg|alt=Model view of Amaravati in APCRDA office|thumb|Model view of Amaravati in APCRDA office]]\nThe Andhra Pradesh State Cabinet meeting passed a resolution of 1 September 2014 to locate the Capital City in a central place of the state, around Vijayawada, and to go for decentralized development of the state with 3 Mega Cities and 14 Smart Cities. The State Government identified the Capital City area between Vijayawada and Guntur cities on the Southern bank of River Krishna upstream of Prakasam Barrage. The Amaravati Capital City has an area of 217.23 km<sup>2</sup> and is spread across 25 villages in 3 mandals (Thulluru, Mangalagiri and Tadepalli) of Guntur district. The 25 villages in the Capital City area have about 1 lakh population in about 27,000 households. The nearest cities are Vijayawada at a distance of 30 km and Guntur at a distance of 18 km. The nearest railway station is KC Canal railway station near Tadepalli and the nearest airport is Gannavaram which is at a distance of 22 km. The city is planned to spread over 217 km<sup>2</sup> area with a total cost of \u20b9 553.43 billions to the Capital Region Development Authority (CRDA) out of which state government contribution is only \u20b9 126 billion (equity \u20b9 66.29 billion and supporting grant \u20b9 59.71 billion) spread over a period of 8 years from April 2018 to March 2026 (\u20b9 5 billion in 2018\u201319, \u20b9 18 billion per year for later six years and \u20b9 13 billion in 2025\u201326).<ref name=\"amr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eenadu.net/eenadu-exclusive/newsarticle/general/1500/120008374|title=Amaravati city a self financed project |language=Telugu|access-date=18 January 2020}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Andhra Pradesh Capital Region Development Authority (APCRDA)\n|'''City area details:'''\n|'''Land utilization'''\n|-\n|Roads, public utilities, parks, natural streams, water bodies\n|27,885 acres\n|-\n|Plots for residential area allotted to the Land contributors(Farmers)\n|11,826 acres\n|-\n|For the needs of other developments presently owned by the CRDA\n|14,037 acres\n|-\n|Total area under the jurisdiction of CRDA\n|53,748 acres\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Amaravati City Land Usage\n!Land use\n!Area (Sq.&nbsp;km)\n!'''%'''\n|-\n|Residential\n|60.77\n|27.9\n|-\n|Commercial\n|20.99\n|9.34\n|-\n|Public and Semi Public\n|11.49\n|5.29\n|-\n|Open spaces and Recreation\n|52.78\n|24.29\n|-\n|Industrial\n|12.26\n|5.64\n|-\n|Water Bodies\n|25.78\n|11.87\n|-\n|Traffic and Transportation\n|23.04\n|10.61\n|-\n|Cultural Heritage\n|0.15\n|0.07\n|-\n|Seed Capital\n|10.67\n|4.91\n|-\n|Total\n|217.23\n|100\n|}\nThe contribution from the government is to be repaid by the CRDA after the year 2037. Ultimately state or union governments are not incurring any expenditure to construct the city but wholly financed by the income accrued from the sale of land for various development schemes (\u20b9 171.51 billion), loans and the local taxes (\u20b9 146.41 billion by 2037) to the CRDA. The state and union governments are expected to earn \u20b9 120 billion per annum out of which state goods and services tax (State GST) alone is \u20b9 60 billion per annum.<ref name=\"amr\" /> The entire city construction is planned by self-financing from loans and land selling with the state government's moral support. CRDA is expecting a net surplus income of \u20b9 333 billion by 2037 after meeting the total expenditure on the city. Amaravati government complex which is intended to provide world-class facilities needed for the state government and its employees' accommodation is also part of CRDA project.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://crda.ap.gov.in/APCRDADOCS/DataModuleFIles/Reports/01~Amaravati%20Project%20Report%20Edition%20No4%20Status%20Feb%202019.pdf|title=Amaravati Project progress report, Edition 4, Feb 2019|access-date=18 January 2020}}</ref> The bus rapid transit system (BRTS) in Amaravati to connect with the adjacent Vijayawada and Guntur cities by world-class road network is also part of the CRDA project.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/vijayawada/2018/mar/02/vijayawada-brts-planned-for-amaravati-to-tackle-vehicle-population-growth-1780930.html|title=BRTS planned for Amaravati to tackle vehicle, population growth|access-date=18 January 2020}}</ref> Both Amaravati government complex and BRTS are planned with an expenditure of \u20b9 140 billion.<ref name=\"amr\" />\n\n== Timeline ==\n[[File:Permanent Secretariat Tower 5 under construction in Amaravati (April 2019).jpg|alt=Permanent Secretariat Tower 5 under construction in Amaravati|thumb|Permanent Secretariat Tower 5 under construction in Amaravati April 2019]]\n[[File:Amaravati Secretariat in Velagapudi (January 2019) 1.jpg|alt=Amaravati Secretariat in Velagapudi|thumb|Amaravati Secretariat in Velagapudi]]\n[[File:Raft foundation works of Andhra Pradesh secretariat in Amaravati (January 2019) 4.jpg|alt=Raft foundation works of Andhra Pradesh secretariat in Amaravati |thumb|Raft foundation works of Andhra Pradesh secretariat in Amaravati ]]\n[[File:Government complex under construction near Rayapudi (January 2019) 12.jpg|alt=Government complex under construction near Rayapudi |thumb|Government complex under construction near Rayapudi ]]\n[[File:Construction equipment at Government complex in Amaravati (January 2019) 4.jpg|alt=Construction equipment at Government complex in Amaravati (January 2019|thumb|Construction equipment at Government complex in Amaravati (January 2019)]]\n[[File:NGO housing under construction in Amaravati (March 2019) 12.jpg|alt=NGO housing under construction in Amaravati (March 2019)|thumb|NGO housing under construction in Amaravati (March 2019)]]\n[[File:Panorama showing constructions along seed access road (November 2018).jpg|alt=Constructions along seed access road|thumb|Constructions along seed access road]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Date\n!Event\n|-\n|2014\n|2 June 2014\n|AP Reorganization Act comes into force.\n|-\n|\n|1 September 201